{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496383"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:45:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1345"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1345"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.12,0.2,0.05,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1345"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105834"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1345"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1345"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88303"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"651"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2271"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2290"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105834"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EYou are an intern managing a 78-year-old woman who was initiated on a thiazide diuretic for congestive heart failure last week. She has developed weakness and muscles spasms, and a blood test demonstrates a potassium of 1.9mmol/L. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What other electrolyte is the most important to test for in the context of hypokalaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Magnesium","Calcium","Sodium","Phosphate","Chloride"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has severe hypokalaemia. Their magnesium levels must be checked, as IV \u003Cstrong\u003Emagnesium \u003C/strong\u003Eis required if the patient is hypomagnesaemic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMagnesium is an important cofactor potassium reabsorption. If both magnesium and potassium are low, the kidney will preferentially retain magnesium, making hypokalaemia very difficult to correct in the context of hypomagnesaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient has been recently commenced on a thiazide diuretic, it is possible that they may also have hyponatraemia; however, this is not very likely, and also is not as pertinent as magnesium in the management of hypokalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThiazide diuretics can also cause hypercalcaemia by increasing kidney reabsorption of calcium; however, this is not important in the context of hypokalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhosphate is unlikely to be altered in this patient, and is not relevant to the treatment of hypokalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThiazides can cause hypochloraemia; however, this is uncommon. Chloride levels are rarely elevated in healthy patients; changes in chloride concentrations are usually largely related to dysregulation in fluid balances (e.g. vomiting, burns). Sometimes, patients with thiazide diuretics have hypokalaemic, hypochloraemic, metabolic alkalosis that responds to potassium chloride replacement; however, measurement levels of chloride are unlikely to change management plans, and are not as important in management as magnesium levels are.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypomagnesaemia must be considered in patients with hypokalaemia, particularly if they have severe hypokalaemia (\u003C2.5mEq/L) or are unresponsive to potassium replacement therapy."],"references":["Kardalas E, Paschou SA, Anagnostis P, Muscogiuri G, Siasos G, Vryonidou A. Hypokalemia: a clinical update. Endocr Connect. (2018) 7:R135\u201346. 10.1530/EC-18-0109"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88303"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1345"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88303"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T09:58:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T09:58:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1345"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105834"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/651"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Hypokalaemia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-10T15:27:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}